# 

<span key="042ee8fbe7b74722a7f5569d180c1f08"><span offset-key="042ee8fbe7b74722a7f5569d180c1f08:0">A Portfolio of Experiences</span></span>

<span key="9832a52df91a40de86ccdd878b5f0f06"><span offset-key="9832a52df91a40de86ccdd878b5f0f06:0">You might be inclined to think of Labs as a "capstone project," with the goal to produce a project to include in your portfolio. </span>*This is not exactly the case*<span offset-key="9832a52df91a40de86ccdd878b5f0f06:2">.</span></span>

<span key="f431a464670846faa7e8597105d9c21f"><span offset-key="f431a464670846faa7e8597105d9c21f:0">In some ways, Labs is like a capstone projectâ€”it's a final, culminating experience where you put everything you've learned into practice. <span key="ecee1bf664634af293c01fc0933d16d3"><span offset-key="ecee1bf664634af293c01fc0933d16d3:0">But ultimately, Labs is really not about creating something to add to a portfolio. This is because </span>**you don't need a running application to demo in an interview.**</span>

<span key="42f9d1bd2ac3487e9ffe0777478ce14b"><span offset-key="42f9d1bd2ac3487e9ffe0777478ce14b:0">Instead, </span>**your skills, experience, and code contributions** ***are*** **your portfolio.**</span>

<span key="27ec6999721b4e0d9be444388f7d11af"><span offset-key="27ec6999721b4e0d9be444388f7d11af:0">Software engineering (data scientists are software engineers, too!) is a collaborative exercise, where team members contribute their skills, experience, and time to collectively create a product. The products that you've contributed to are rarely themselves important (</span>*particularly*<span offset-key="27ec6999721b4e0d9be444388f7d11af:2"> for entry-level positions).</span></span>

<span key="4cb7515340974494863c7223d9e976d8"><span offset-key="4cb7515340974494863c7223d9e976d8:0">Experience</span></span>

# 

<span key="ae8ba870eb7d4509bd487091594c9e0c"><span offset-key="ae8ba870eb7d4509bd487091594c9e0c:0">SDLC: How We Develop in Labs</span></span>

<span key="a4ddc49b3c9b4bc3994028b68ee3a991"><span offset-key="a4ddc49b3c9b4bc3994028b68ee3a991:0">Both in Labs and on the job, your work will follow (or at least be a critical part of) a repeating cycle: the </span>**software development lifecycle**<span offset-key="a4ddc49b3c9b4bc3994028b68ee3a991:2"> (SDLC).</span></span>

## 

<span key="be1118e684c34f6e812c79d94be7a8cb"><span offset-key="be1118e684c34f6e812c79d94be7a8cb:0">Agile Methodologies</span></span>

<span key="89e1b82515e945a2bb13bd793b4f4e0a"><span offset-key="89e1b82515e945a2bb13bd793b4f4e0a:0">In 2001, a group of software developers got together and penned </span></span><a href="https://agilemanifesto.org" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="d434e9837dac459d91466238f63d4b5c" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-5625_259-5626-237__"><span data-key="0061a0eb4984499a9697708c97e82828"><span data-offset-key="0061a0eb4984499a9697708c97e82828:0">the Agile Manifesto (Links to an external site.)</span></span></span></a><span key="54c05d4031974ac691363aaafd02a533"><span offset-key="54c05d4031974ac691363aaafd02a533:0"> (yeah... that's how webpages looked in 2001). The Agile Manifesto put forth some key concepts for what to prioritize during software development:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="ac77e8bc617c4400b94f0970bb25114d">**Individuals and interactions**<span offset-key="ac77e8bc617c4400b94f0970bb25114d:1"> over processes and tools</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="e8a69f7939a84228a9c58514eacf1f29">**Working software**<span offset-key="e8a69f7939a84228a9c58514eacf1f29:1"> over comprehensive documentation</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="d23ad1f1ae1c49e98581e5eacb6805d3">**Customer collaboration**<span offset-key="d23ad1f1ae1c49e98581e5eacb6805d3:1"> over contract negotiation</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="28e526a82e7942da844f0b60accacb2c">**Responding to change**<span offset-key="28e526a82e7942da844f0b60accacb2c:1"> over following a plan</span></span>

<span key="abe1578ee07a4d4ca6864b89a5ced495"><span offset-key="abe1578ee07a4d4ca6864b89a5ced495:0">In shortâ€”bias toward action, in small, management chunks of work, and remain responsive to the many sources of change that will throw wrenches into even the best-laid plans.</span></span>

<span key="f19fc6d3b0d6491eb9ae3ed92a9a7a91"><span offset-key="f19fc6d3b0d6491eb9ae3ed92a9a7a91:0">You might also hear agile methodologies called a "lean" approach to software development. The idea is that, sure, we could try to produce a really detailed plan with steps looking ahead a long period of time ("</span>**waterfall**<span offset-key="f19fc6d3b0d6491eb9ae3ed92a9a7a91:2">" development) and/or build everything at once (sometimes called "</span>**big bang**<span offset-key="f19fc6d3b0d6491eb9ae3ed92a9a7a91:4">" development)â€”but ultimately, it's much faster, easier, and more effective to </span>**iterate**<span offset-key="f19fc6d3b0d6491eb9ae3ed92a9a7a91:6">â€”repeat a very short, very simple series of steps, with each cycle building on the last.</span></span>

<span key="97eb815e1f9945da82c56d9ec47e57a7"><span offset-key="97eb815e1f9945da82c56d9ec47e57a7:0">That cycle is the software development lifecycle, and with an agile approach, it's short and sweet.</span></span>

## 

<span key="78b67d85f906438fb1a741b0b6af3e2b"><span offset-key="78b67d85f906438fb1a741b0b6af3e2b:0">The Software Development Lifecycle</span></span>

<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1rasi3h" />

Could not load image

<span key="0e668dafaaf34bd489826c070cc2841e"><span offset-key="0e668dafaaf34bd489826c070cc2841e:0">Labs Software Development Lifecycle: Planning, Designing, Building, Evaluating. These repeat with connecting arrows.</span></span>

<span key="756fb61ac5574f7e904136873c32b83b"><span offset-key="756fb61ac5574f7e904136873c32b83b:0">Ultimately, all types of software development will follow a cyclical pattern. There are many different ways to think about the stages of the SDLC, but for our purposes in Labs, let's go with these:</span></span>

1.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">1.</span>
    <span key="2b58e4515c154280ae7c71560aada2a7">**Planning:**<span offset-key="2b58e4515c154280ae7c71560aada2a7:1"> Determining what to build</span></span>

2.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">2.</span>
    <span key="fab49021c7084d0fba01a957ddfa66de">**Designing:**<span offset-key="fab49021c7084d0fba01a957ddfa66de:1"> Determining how to build it</span></span>

3.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">3.</span>
    <span key="109cf11b1c0643008f3330757e7dbf1f">**Building:**<span offset-key="109cf11b1c0643008f3330757e7dbf1f:1"> ...I mean, yeah, actually building it</span></span>

4.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">4.</span>
    <span key="4b2de582099f45d997177a1e91558d47">**Evaluating:**<span offset-key="4b2de582099f45d997177a1e91558d47:1"> Determining how the process went (including testing)</span></span>

<span key="0e76f7e7e86b460b82630d5b4e7350be"><span offset-key="0e76f7e7e86b460b82630d5b4e7350be:0">In agile development, each cycle is a </span>**sprint**<span offset-key="0e76f7e7e86b460b82630d5b4e7350be:2">, and we go through each stage during each cycle. Rinse, repeat.</span></span>

<span key="cc4c2f1a36994681934c5b3579ab4708"><span offset-key="cc4c2f1a36994681934c5b3579ab4708:0">In Labs, you'll follow this cycle by:</span></span>

1.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">1.</span>
    <span key="2fbaea4e20214d78b71d6669a6689aab">**Planning:**<span offset-key="2fbaea4e20214d78b71d6669a6689aab:1"> Working with the Technical Project Managers on your team to scope each sprint</span></span>

2.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">2.</span>
    <span key="293894cde4e34caa8e685442759fc6a9">**Designing:**<span offset-key="293894cde4e34caa8e685442759fc6a9:1"> Working with all roles on your team to develop lean artifacts like diagrams, API contracts, and implementation plans</span></span>

3.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">3.</span>
    <span key="dffaeb678306486cbba2996d4323b50b">**Building**<span offset-key="dffaeb678306486cbba2996d4323b50b:1">: Collaborating cross-functionally to write code and deploy infrastructure</span></span>

4.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">4.</span>
    <span key="3d161ce635c3473e977fc78f59fc0564">**Evaluating:**<span offset-key="3d161ce635c3473e977fc78f59fc0564:1"> Writing unit and integration tests, looking back on the sprint for lessons learned, and factoring those lessons into the next cycle</span></span>

<span key="5ef95fdba8934599a6b07c7402dfac63"><span offset-key="5ef95fdba8934599a6b07c7402dfac63:0">Labs Best Practices & Tips for Success</span></span>

<span key="a65aed29636a4d2fbde80ee651efbc0e"><span offset-key="a65aed29636a4d2fbde80ee651efbc0e:0">Okâ€”now you know how Labs works, the goal of Labs, how the SDLC works, and where to find the Labs standards. But what does success in Labs look likeâ€”and how do you achieve it?</span></span>

## 

<span key="bb70acc8216a4aa7b875aec29655e69a"><span offset-key="bb70acc8216a4aa7b875aec29655e69a:0">Communication</span></span>

<span key="0c40c1b1aa32481d985455881fdc4419"><span offset-key="0c40c1b1aa32481d985455881fdc4419:0">Get ready to hear this </span>*over and over*<span offset-key="0c40c1b1aa32481d985455881fdc4419:2"> from here on out: </span>**communication is the key to producing great software.**<span offset-key="0c40c1b1aa32481d985455881fdc4419:4"> If your mind goes blank in an interview and there's only one word you can remember, make sure it's "communication."</span></span>

<span key="5e8f755dcf65449b84c58a38eeae6f55"><span offset-key="5e8f755dcf65449b84c58a38eeae6f55:0">Communication comes in many forms:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="32ced465d55e4f5e8846c968e64e28ad"><span offset-key="32ced465d55e4f5e8846c968e64e28ad:0">You'll need to communicate with your </span>**stakeholder**<span offset-key="32ced465d55e4f5e8846c968e64e28ad:2"> to present your progress in detail; ask targeted, clarifying questions; and emerge with a solid vision of their user requirements.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="871ac268dd184ecbb89020c9476efce8"><span offset-key="871ac268dd184ecbb89020c9476efce8:0">You'll need to communicate with your </span>**Product Manager**<span offset-key="871ac268dd184ecbb89020c9476efce8:2"> about the scope, objectives, and priorities of your product.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="ed9703f699bf4001908e5f765029c2c5"><span offset-key="ed9703f699bf4001908e5f765029c2c5:0">You'll need to communicate with your </span>**Design Manager**<span offset-key="ed9703f699bf4001908e5f765029c2c5:2"> to collaboratively approach design problems and iterate solutions.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="465071a3e860423593c8c43e12301ea5"><span offset-key="465071a3e860423593c8c43e12301ea5:0">You'll need to communicate with your </span>**Engineering and Data Science Managers**<span offset-key="465071a3e860423593c8c43e12301ea5:2"> for guidance on implementation and to resolve issues (after first troubleshooting with your team!).</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="628135c2b5204af5a2a72c8125661528"><span offset-key="628135c2b5204af5a2a72c8125661528:0">You'll need to communicate with your </span>**Release Manager**<span offset-key="628135c2b5204af5a2a72c8125661528:2"> by walking them through your pull requests and reaching out for support.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="74f8fa0882b84001a4e05e06277bf7ab"><span offset-key="74f8fa0882b84001a4e05e06277bf7ab:0">You'll need to communicate with </span>**future developers**<span offset-key="74f8fa0882b84001a4e05e06277bf7ab:2"> on your product by including solid documentation.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="aa8532b415924ff58d04b16c7d3b8be3"><span offset-key="aa8532b415924ff58d04b16c7d3b8be3:0">But most importantly, you'll need to communicate </span>**cross-functionally with your team**<span offset-key="aa8532b415924ff58d04b16c7d3b8be3:2"> (and across teams!) to keep development moving forward in unison.</span></span>

<span key="376924b76fce4d58851616b2e34d76ba"><span offset-key="376924b76fce4d58851616b2e34d76ba:0">Do all of these throughout Labs, and you will succeed.</span></span>

## 

<span key="7527051affee44cfa66c739564d3d838"><span offset-key="7527051affee44cfa66c739564d3d838:0">Professionalism</span></span>

<span key="16dc73f99ec34d88abfb3b5d02cad4cb"><span offset-key="16dc73f99ec34d88abfb3b5d02cad4cb:0">In virtually every way, Labs is designed both to equip you to land a job and to prepare you for the job itself. (What use would it be to be able to get a job, but not keep it?)</span></span>

<span key="586368bfd7c34de3a6f1f4622ac0501e">**Professionalism**<span offset-key="586368bfd7c34de3a6f1f4622ac0501e:1"> factors into both of these critical goals. Ask yourself: what does professionalism mean to you?</span></span>

<span key="dc14f51f015c4372bdcf9960fb795af8"><span offset-key="dc14f51f015c4372bdcf9960fb795af8:0">Many factors contribute to professionalism in the job search and in the workplace, but here are some of the big things to focus on in Labs to prepare you:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="53e2a93b59184bc8824bf60b3d6432bf">**Show up:**<span offset-key="53e2a93b59184bc8824bf60b3d6432bf:1"> </span>*Be here*<span offset-key="53e2a93b59184bc8824bf60b3d6432bf:3">, and treat Labs like the full-time or part-time job it is. Don't leave your teammates hanging.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="9b80ae86d37d4fa99e825bfb0e07654c">**Cameras on:**<span offset-key="9b80ae86d37d4fa99e825bfb0e07654c:1"> Have you ever spoken to a Zoom room full of faceless squares? Your instructors have ðŸ˜ž But you know what? We can take it! A hiring manager, on the other hand... In Labs, you'll need to keep your camera on to practice the level of interaction a hiring manager will expect.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="5f82926c3299402c87f7efc417a33272">**Participate:**<span offset-key="5f82926c3299402c87f7efc417a33272:1"> Speak up during meetings, ask and respond to questions, commit code every day, and engage critically with your project and the curriculum. </span>**This will help**<span offset-key="5f82926c3299402c87f7efc417a33272:3"> by getting you in the habit of doing the same kinds of things on the job.</span></span>
